c groups in Bosnia and Herzegovina. It examines the transethnic character of cultural heritage, against divisions that dominate their tragic recent past. The monograph focuses in particular on customs shared by different ethnic groups, specifically elopement, and affinal visitation. The elopement is a transformative rite of passage where an unmarried girl becomes a married woman. The affinal visitation, which follows, is a confirmatory ceremony where ritualized customs between families establish in-lawships These customs reflect a transethnic heritage shared by people in Bosnia as a national group, including Bosniaks, Serbs and Croats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aBosniansxMarriage customs and rites. 0aElopementzBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aElopementzBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aElopement--Bosnia and Herzegovina. 0aMarriage customs and riteszBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aMarriage customs and riteszBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aMarriagezBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aMarriagezBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aWomenzBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aWomenzBosnia and Herzegovina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a19th century, 20th century, Bosnia, Elopement, Ethnic relations, Ethnography, Marriage, Women.1 aSlapšak, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633860618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633860618/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPD